Across the landlocked Bolivian coastline, the memory of the coastline lost to Chile in the bloody conflicts of the 19th century is still fresh in the memory - along with the desire to sail through the Pacific again.
These hopes are perhaps the strongest in decades, as Bolivia awaits a ruling from the International Court of Justice in The Hague on October 1 after five years of proceedings.
“Bolivia possesses the power, the spirit of unity and the intransigence, and of course awaits the decision with a positive mind,” said Roberto Calzadilla, a Bolivian diplomat.
