John Edward: Language skills are a necessity for world citizens
The private schools in Scotland are known for the outstanding achievements of their students and it has continued in 2018 with new, impressive test results, which are still supported by individual and group achievements in sports, arts, music and other social practices.
These schools have up to 30,000 students across Scotland, with the Scottish Council of Independent Schools (SCIS) in charge of them, and they strive to provide their students and their parents with the best possible service.
Private schools aim to prepare their students for further postgraduate studies, the career they have chosen and their status as a citizen of the world.
As a teaching sector that can assemble and teach from specially designed curriculums, we see that new language continues to be a popular learning material in schools.
Nelson Mandela said, “If you speak to a man in a language he understands, it touches his mind.
If you speak to him in his native language, it will touch his heart.”
This is an important reminder that we can’t just rely on English to build relationships and trust with people from other countries.
This year’s test results show us that languages are at the top of the list with the highest percentage of students who pass exams in private schools.
Sixty-eight per cent of students who learned foreign languages received a grade A.
The data, collected from 74 schools within SCIS, showed that 72 percent of students received an excellent A in mandarin, while 72 percent of those who learned German, 69 percent of those who learned French and 63 percent of those who learned Spanish also received an A.
This shows that private schools in Scotland support foreign languages as essential skills that children and young people will definitely need in the future.
At the moment, languages, as an elective subject, are placed in the same place as science-related study materials (science, technology, engineering and mathematics) in the curriculum of private schools and elsewhere.
A 2014 poll conducted by the UK Commission for Employment and Skills found that, for reasons stated by employers that it was difficult to find a job, 17 per cent were due to a lack of language skills.
Therefore, language skills are becoming increasingly important in preparing young people for their future jobs.
Now that more and more jobs require language skills, these skills are essential in a globalized world.
No matter what career people choose, learning another language will have a real advantage in the future, but it is a skill that will last a lifetime.
The ability to communicate directly with people from other countries will give a multilingual person an automatic advantage over competitors.
According to a 2013 YouGov survey of over 4,000 adults in Britain, 75 percent of them were unable to speak another language well enough to sustain conversation, and French was the only language spoken by a two-digit percentage, or 15 percent.
Therefore, it is important for children of today to invest immediately in language learning.
Multilingualism, especially in emerging markets, will give children a better chance to find a significant job.
In Scotland, the language they teach varies between schools.
A certain number of schools will focus on classical new languages, while others will teach languages that are considered to be the most important for the UK when looking up to the year 2020, such as Mandarin or Japanese.
No matter where your child’s interest lies, he will always be able to choose from languages in private schools with specialized teachers.
Scottish private schools commit to providing a learning environment that will prepare children and equip them with the skills they need to succeed, no matter what the future holds.
It cannot be denied that at this time, in the global business environment, language continues to be essential for the future of the country, and it must be reflected in education.
In fact, modern language should really be seen as “international communication skills.”
Private schools will continue to offer choice, diversity and superiority for Scotland’s youth.
Il faut bien le faire.
John Edwards is the chairman of the Scottish Private School Council.
