Although Ri has repeated familiar North Korean complaints about Washington’s opposition to a “staged” approach to nuclear disarmament in which North Korea would be rewarded for every step taken, his statement seemed special in that he did not deny unilateral nuclear disarmament purely as Pyongyang had previously done.
Ri referred to the joint statement by Kim Jong Un and Donald Trump at a first meeting between the US president and North Korean leaders in Singapore on June 12, in which Kim pledged to work on “the nuclear disarmament of the Korean peninsula” and Trump pledged to ensure the security of North Korea.
North Korea has sought a solution to end the Korean War in 1950-53, but the United States has said that Pyongyang must abandon its nuclear weapons first.
Washington has also resisted calls to relax a strict embargo on North Korea.
“The United States is demanding ‘nuclear disarmament first’ and increasing pressure by using trade embargoes to achieve its goal, and even protesting the declaration to end the war,” Ri said.
“There are only dreams of people who don’t know anything about us to think that bans can bring us to our knees.
