Harvard students take classes in sufficient rest
A new course at Harvard University has given all students more sleep in an attempt to counteract the growing tendency of students to stay awake and learn all night with the help of caffeine tablets.
A study found that students at the world’s best universities often know little or nothing about the basics of thinking about themselves.
Charles Czeisler, Professor of Sleep Medicine at Harvard Medical School and an expert at Brigham and the Women's Hospital, designed the course and believes it is the first of its kind in the United States.
He got the idea to do the course after giving a lecture on the effects of sleep deprivation on learning ability.
“At the end of the lecture, a girl came to me and asked, ‘Why am I told this first now, in my final year?’
She said no one told her anything about the importance of sleep, which surprised me,” he told Telegraph.
The course, held for the first time this year, explains to students the basics of how good sleeping habits help learning ability and performance in sports and even contribute to general well-being.
Paul Barreira, professor of psychiatry at Harvard Medical School and director of health care, said the university had decided to introduce the course after finding out that students were very sleepless over the week.
The course is an hour long and involves various interactive tasks.
In one section is a picture of a room in a dormitory, where students click on coffee cups, curtains, sports shoes and books to learn about the effects of caffeine and light and how performance in sports can deteriorate with lack of sleep, as well as the importance of a good routine for sleep.
In the second part, participants are told how long-term lack of sleep can increase the risk of heart attack, stroke, depression and cancer.
A map of the school area with interactive icons then encourages participants to think about their daily routines.
“We know that this will not change the behavior of students immediately.
But we think they have a right to know, just as one has a right to know about the health effects of smoking cigarettes,” Professor Czeisler added.
The culture that celebrates those who stay awake and learn all night is still there, he said, adding that modern technology and ever-increasing pressure on students meant sleep deprivation was a growing problem.
Ensuring good quality sleep should be a “secret weapon” for students to protect against stress, fatigue and anxiety, he said – even to avoid gaining weight, because lack of sleep increases the brain’s call for food so that the body is constantly hungry.
Raymond So, a 19-year-old student in chemistry and physics from California, helped Professor Czeisler put the course together, who sat one of the professor’s cursus last year in his first year at Harvard.
He said the course had opened his eyes and encouraged him to call for a course for all the students in the school.
He hopes that the next step will be to ask all master students to complete a similar course before they start studying at the university.
Professor Czeisler recommended that students consider setting an alarm clock, which reminds them to go to sleep, and to wake them up, bearing in mind the harmful effects of blue light emitted by electronic displays and LED lights, which can confuse the internal clock of the body and lead to trouble falling asleep.
