New Cancer Vaccine May Teach Your Immune System to 'See' Dangerous Cells
A new anti-cancer vaccine may teach the immune system to “see” dangerous cells and kill them
The vaccine teaches your immune system to recognize dangerous cells as part of your treatment
The treatment involves taking immune cells from the patient and transforming them in the laboratory
They can then “see” the protein, which is common in many cancer cells, and is then injected back into the patient.
Vaccines at the experimental stage have shown positive results in patients suffering from different types of cancer.
In one woman who received the vaccine, ovarian cancer disappeared for more than 18 months. The vaccine teaches immune cells to recognize dangerous cancer cells.
The method involves taking immune cells from a patient and transforming them in a laboratory so that they can “see” a protein called HER2 found in many types of cancer. Then the cells are injected back into the patient.
