Europe wins Ryder Cup in Paris
The European team has won the 2018 Ryder Cup by defeating the US team with a final score of 16.5 to 10.5 points at Le Golf National outside Paris, France.
The United States has now lost six consecutive European losses and has not won the Ryder Cup in Europe since 1993.
Europe regained the crown when the team, led by Danish captain Thomas Bjorn, reached the 14.5 points needed to defeat the United States.
American star Phil Mickelson, who suffered most of the race, hit the 16th hole in the water and lost his game to Francesco Molinari.
Italian golfer Molinari shone sharply in all his games and became 1 of 4 players to get the result 5-0-0, since the race began using its current format in 1979.
Jordan Spieth lost 5&4 to Thorbjorn Olesen from Denmark, who was in the lowest position in the European rankings.
Dustin Johnson, the world's top golfer, lost 2 and 1 to England's Ian Poulter, who may have played in his last Ryder Cup competition.
Spain's Sergio Garcia, who has played eight times for the Ryder Cup, became the most successful European champion with 25.5 career points.
“I don’t usually cry, but today I can’t do anything else.
It has been a difficult year.
I am so thankful to Thomas for choosing me and believing in me.
I am so happy to have the cup back.
It's about the team, and it was a pleasure to be able to help," said Garcia after the European victory.
He won his countryman John Rahm's torch, defeating the American golf legend Tiger Woods 2&1 in a singles match on Sunday.
"I was incredibly proud to have defeated Tiger Woods, I grew up watching him," Rahm said.
Woods lost all four of his games in France and is now registered with 13-21-3 in the competition for the Ryder Cup.
This is a strange conclusion for one of the best players in history, who has won 14 major titles and is only in second place behind Jack Nicklaus.
